If you wish to intercept and log data being sent from a website using XMLHttpRequest (XHR), you can override the `send` function of the `XMLHttpRequest` prototype. Here's a JavaScript example of how to achieve this in the browser:

```javascript
// Keep a reference to the original XMLHttpRequest.send function
const originalSend = XMLHttpRequest.prototype.send;

// Override the XMLHttpRequest.send function
XMLHttpRequest.prototype.send = function(body) {
    // You can log, modify or perform any action with the data (body) here
    console.log('XHR data being sent:', body);

    // Call the original send function with the (potentially modified) data
    originalSend.call(this, body);
};
```

This code snippet will log the data being sent with every XHR request in the console. Note that this should be done before any XHR requests are made; putting this snippet in the `<head>` section of your HTML or at the very top of your script will usually suffice.

Keep in mind that overriding native browser functions can potentially break the website if not done correctly. Also, depending on how the website is implemented, there may be additional security measures in place (such as Content Security Policy) that might restrict this kind of behavior, especially with third-party scripts.

When using this technique for development purposes, ensure that it complies with the website's security policy and privacy considerations, and avoid using it on production sites without proper authorization.

Yes, before native JavaScript classes were introduced in ES6 (ECMAScript 2015), developers would use functions to simulate class-like behavior. Here is a polyfill that can replicate basic class functionality using functions and prototypes:

```javascript
function MyClass(arg1, arg2) {
  // Constructor logic
  this.property1 = arg1;
  this.property2 = arg2;
}

// Simulate methods by adding them to the prototype
MyClass.prototype.myMethod = function() {
  // Some method logic
  console.log(this.property1);
};

// Simulate static methods by adding them directly to the constructor function
MyClass.staticMethod = function() {
  // Some static method logic
  console.log('This is a static method.');
};

// Simulate inheritance using prototype chaining
function MySubClass(arg1, arg2, arg3) {
  // Call the parent constructor
  MyClass.call(this, arg1, arg2);

  // Additional constructor logic for the subclass
  this.property3 = arg3;
}

// Create a new object whose prototype is MyClass.prototype
MySubClass.prototype = Object.create(MyClass.prototype);

// Set the constructor property of the new prototype to MySubClass
MySubClass.prototype.constructor = MySubClass;

// Now you can add methods to MySubClass prototype just like MyClass
MySubClass.prototype.mySubClassMethod = function() {
  // Subclass method logic
  console.log(this.property3);
};

// Usage:
var instance = new MyClass('value1', 'value2');
instance.myMethod(); // Logs 'value1'

var subInstance = new MySubClass('value1', 'value2', 'value3');
subInstance.mySubClassMethod(); // Logs 'value3'
subInstance.myMethod(); // Logs 'value1' 
```

This is how developers emulated classes before ES6. The `MyClass` function serves as the constructor, and methods are added to `MyClass.prototype` for shared behaviors. Static methods are added directly to the `MyClass` function. For inheritance, you create a new function, as seen with `MySubClass`, and use `Object.create` to inherit from the parent class prototype.

Keep in mind that native ES6 classes offer more features such as class expressions, getters and setters, super calls, class static initialization blocks, and more. A polyfill might not support all class features provided by ES6, but the above example should cover the basics of constructor functions and prototypical inheritance.
